 tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWorld-wide migration has an unsettling effect on social structures, especially on aging populations and eldercare. This volume investigates how taken-for-granted roles are challenged, intergenerational relationships transformed, economic ties recalibrated, technological innovations utilized, and spiritual relations pursued and desired, and asks what it means to care at a distance and to age abroad. What it does show is that trans-nationalization of care produces unprecedented convergences of people, objects and spaces that challenge our assumptions about the who, how, and where of care.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aAgingxSocial aspectsvCase studies. 0aEmigration and immigrationxSocial aspectsvCase studies. 0aImmigrant familiesvCase studies. 0aOlder peoplexCarexSocial aspectsvCase studies. 0aOlder peoplexSocial conditionsvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh1 aChoedup, Namgyal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDesai, Retika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHromadžic, Azra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHromadžić, Azra, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKaiser-Grolimund, Andrea Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLamb, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiles, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalmberger, Monika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalmberger, Monika, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPijl, Yvon van der, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.